Good idea—having matching web variables keeps your digital and PDF versions visually unified.  
Here’s a quick CSS snippet you can drop into a stylesheet or an online‑form builder’s “custom colors” section:

```css
:root {
  /* Core palette */
  --color-teal: #3DA6A6;        /* headings, primary lines */
  --color-blue-muted: #5B7FA5;  /* subheadings, hints */
  --color-sage: #BFD8C6;        /* dividers, footer accents */
  --color-sand: #DAD1C4;        /* optional warm background */
  --color-text-main: #222222;   /* main body text */
  --color-text-muted: #666666;  /* footer or secondary text */
  --color-bg: #FAFAFA;          /* neutral page background */

  /* Accessibility helpers */
  --line-height-base: 1.5;
  --font-heading: "Lato", "Montserrat", sans-serif;
  --font-body: "Open Sans", "Source Sans Pro", sans-serif;
}

/* Example usage */
body {
  font-family: var(--font-body);
  color: var(--color-text-main);
  background-color: var(--color-bg);
  line-height: var(--line-height-base);
}

h1, h2, h3 {
  font-family: var(--font-heading);
  color: var(--color-teal);
}

hr.divider {
  border: 0;
  border-top: 1px solid var(--color-sage);
}
footer {
  color: var(--color-text-muted);
  border-top: 1px solid var(--color-sage);
}
.note {
  color: var(--color-blue-muted);
  font-style: italic;
}
```

Each variable links directly to the print values you’ve already set (the CMYK equivalents still hold for PDFs).  
You can tweak brightness slightly if your site uses a dark background—all accents maintain WCAG contrast above 4.5 : 1 on white.  

